Answers














Best Answer: 
             Short Answer - Standard Deviation 

Your concept is correct – here is more detail: 

Walter Shewhart was the first person to develop something called control charts (in the 1930's), which utilize plus/minus six standard deviations from the mean of a group (population) of numbers.  Thus you could call this "Plus and Minus Three Sigma {Standard Deviations}" or "Six Sigma" 

However the term "Six Sigma" was first utilized by Motorola as a marketing ploy in helping them win the Malcolm Baldrige National Quality Award in 1988.  As part of winning the award, all awardees must be open to presenting best practices to anyone who asks and the term "Six Sigma" was born.  It did not become popular until the mid-1990's after GE become successful in applying the Motorola methodology and integrating Six Sigma into their own existing processes. 

The all but forgotten fact is that back in 1988; Motorola was actually using the Shewhart definition of plus and minus three standard deviations.  Which was rejected by Ford Motor Company in the early 1990's because using that definition, did not meet the requirements for the Automotive Industry which was/is plus/minus four standard deviations for ongoing production products and plus/minus five standard deviations for prototype products. 

It wasn't until the late 1990's that the term "Six Sigma" came to represent plus/minus six standard deviations (which it still means today), however, even this is not totally true as the Six Sigma proponents use a variation (shifting factor) calculation that reduces the theoretical value to something less than the true value of six standard deviations. 




 Source(s): 
 http://www.asq.org 
http://www.nist.gov 
I lived this history and was the guy at Ford who rejected the Motorola process in the early 1990's as well as being the Training Director for Ford in the late 1990's who lead training for 3000 Six Sigma Black Belts 


sixsigmaboss
 · 8 years ago 





